olive oil
2 leek
1 onion
2 clove garlic
1 tomato
1 packet spaghetti
1 packet diced bacon
10 g butter
½ tsp plain flour
½ bottle cream
½ sachet Chicken-Style Stock Powder
½ tsp honey
1 bag salad leaves
1 packet Grated Parmesan Cheese
1 tsp vinegar (balsamic or white wine)

Bring a large saucepan of salted water to the boil.
Cook the spaghetti in the boiling water, stirring
occasionally, until 'al dente', 10 minutes. Reserve
some pasta water, then drain the spaghetti and
return to the pan. Drizzle with olive oil to
prevent sticking.

TIP: 'Al dente' pasta is cooked through but still
slightly firm in the centre.

While the spaghetti is cooking, thinly slice the
onion. Thinly slice the white and light green parts
of the leek. Finely chop the garlic. Roughly chop
the tomato.

Heat a large frying pan over a medium-high heat
with a drizzle of olive oil. Cook the leek and diced
bacon, breaking up the bacon with a spoon, until
golden, 5-6 minutes.

Add the onion, garlic and the butter to the frying
pan and cook until fragrant, 1 minute. Add the
plain flour and cook, stirring, 1 minute. Reduce
the heat to low, then add the longlife cream (see
ingredients) and grated Parmesan cheese. Add
the chicken-style stock powder (see ingredients)
and stir until combined. Add the cooked spaghetti,
then gently stir to coat. Season with pepper.

TIP: Add a dash of the reserved pasta water if the
sauce seems too thick.

In a large bowl, combine the vinegar, the honey
and a drizzle of olive oil. Season, then add the
mixed leaves and tomato. Toss to coat.

Divide the creamy bacon and leek spaghetti
between bowls. Serve with the garden salad.